# Project: Wedding planning SaaS (couples + planners)

## Stack
- Next.js (App Router, TypeScript, React Server Components)
- Supabase (Postgres, Auth, Row Level Security)
- Tailwind CSS
- Data: Supabase server client in server components for reads; server actions for writes

## Architecture principles (do not violate)
- Multi-tenant. A "couple" is an account that owns exactly ONE project (a wedding).
  A "planner" is an account that owns MANY projects (one per client).
  NEVER fork the data model or UI by audience — it's the same model, different counts.
- Everything scopes to a project via `project_id`.
- Authorization lives in the DATABASE via RLS, never in app code. The SQL function
  `can_access_project(uuid)` is the single access rule. Do NOT write "and the user
  owns this" filters in queries, and do NOT add manual permission checks in components
  or actions. RLS enforces access; trust it.
- Before writing any query, READ the schema in `supabase/migrations/`. Do not invent
  tables or columns. If a feature needs a new column, write a new migration file.

## Data access conventions
- Server components read via the Supabase server client, scoped by `project_id`.
- Mutations are server actions (`'use server'`) that write by `id` or `project_id`
  and call `revalidatePath` afterward. RLS silently blocks unauthorized writes.
- Never expose or use the service-role key anywhere reachable by the browser.
  Use the anon key plus the user's session only.

## Code conventions
- TypeScript strict. Generate types with `supabase gen types typescript` and use them.
- Server components by default. Add `'use client'` only for interactive bits
  (status toggles, forms, inline edits).
- Keep components small, colocated under `components/<feature>/`.
- No localStorage or sessionStorage.

## Out of bounds
- No auth/permission logic in app code.
- No new tables/columns without a migration in `supabase/migrations/`.
- Build only what the current prompt asks for — do not scaffold future slices ahead of time.